reviews.review_text: Motorcycle drums This is one of the Greek Theater shows where they had a biker in there during drums and space. Mickey seems to be telling the guy to let it idle "leave it there." It's a nice clear sounding recording but like the previous motorcyle Not Fade Away in '78 to my ears it sounds like it gets over-saturated in the louder parts (a motorcylce revving being a "louder part"). Still marvelous to hear.
Decent Not my favorite setlist, but some may enjoy it more if these are some of their favs. Certainly a good show, but nothing blew my mind.
Not sure why I gave this 5 stars I'm not sure why I originally gave this 5 stars. Maybe the novelty of the biker? I don't know. Some nice songs in the set, but I'd like to revise this.

On The Day In Grateful Dead History This is a very nice, well recorded and mixed (Thank You CM) 1982 show.  
The first set is great. IMHO a great Shakedown Street and Brent singing Red Rooster.  Let It Grow is not my favorite first set closer but this is also a great performance.

The second set starts with a less strong SB/FOTM but moves along nicely. Ship Of Fools -> Estimated Prophet  -> Eyes of the World is very tight. We COULD live without another CJ but even this one used as the closer is nicely sung by a very relaxed JG.  Encore is a fun Rolling Stone: I can't get do (Satisfaction) and the much loved Breakdown Palace.
Must Hear Concert.

Pristine sound. Great show.Thank you @Charlie Miller.Listen Loud & #dontletgo
Brent's Softail 33 years ago today these crazy mofos were mic'n up Brent's Harley. Roosters heavy too.

its all greek to me The Greek theatre was a special place for numerous reasons. relatively small, AMAZING acoustics which is why there are so many good/excellant aud tapes from there over the years. it was a 'home' show. you had the awesome claremont hotel just up the road and it was always a BIG party.

Its like Ramrod use to say 'there's the Bay area, New York then everywhere else.'

im also curious if that explains why theses SBD tapes are some of the best of the year with good fat bass and bass response. although a lot of the SBD's from the 2nd half of 82 are good, bass, good mix, etc

Greek Magic  This whole 3day run was excellent imo! The 22nd I heard on dead hour w/David Gan's right after and was amazed by the supplication, deal, China Rider, all so tight, like this last night show. Also the Greek was such a Killer venue, like the Frost it was sad when they had to stop playing there.
And I'm curious as to why these SBD are all so, just about perfect?!! The separation & sound is better then what Dave's picks sound like Lol. Wish more of 82 and even more so Fall 1983 & 1984 had boards this clean & balanced! It would make fall 83 & 84 even better.

energy I believe this was the first time I personally saw the new Meyer sound system and was blown away how it could be that loud and that clean. No ringing ears after the show.I still remember the way the crowd was pulsing with the sound waves during Scarlet. I'll hold this version of Scarlet up against any out there. The mix is incredible, especially how up from Weir is.

University The Grateful Dead performed live at the Greek Theatre, University of California on May 23, 1982. The Greek Theatre is a renowned outdoor amphitheater located on the campus of the University of California, Berkeley.

The Grateful Dead, known for their improvisational style and blending of various music genres, captivated audiences with their unique sound and energetic live performances. Their shows were characterized by extended jam sessions and a dedicated fan base known as "Deadheads."

The concert on May 23, 1982, featured the Grateful Dead's iconic lineup, including Jerry Garcia, Bob Weir, Phil Lesh, Bill Kreutzmann, Mickey Hart, and Brent Mydland. The band played a diverse setlist that showcased their eclectic repertoire, incorporating elements of rock, folk, blues, and psychedelic music.
